100 Years Ago Today, This is What Was Happening ...

On January 10, 1926, the British government announced its decision to halt the construction of a new naval base at Scapa Flow, citing budgetary constraints. In France, tensions escalated as the government faced increasing criticism over its handling of the Ruhr crisis, with calls for stronger action against German non-compliance. Meanwhile, in the United States, discussions continued around the impending Dempsey-Tunney boxing match, which promised to capture national attention in the coming weeks.
